* Key Pattern Flags (Modifiers)
  Used to change matching behavior:

  - Pattern.CASE_INSENSITIVE → ignore case
  - Pattern.MULTILINE → ^ and $ match start/end of each line
  - Pattern.DOTALL → . matches newline too
  - Pattern.UNICODE_CASE, Pattern.COMMENTS, etc.

* Common Methods in Matcher
 - matches() → entire string must match pattern
 - find() → finds next subsequence that matches (for partial matches)
 - lookingAt() → matches from start, but doesn’t require full string
 - group() → returns matched substring
 - replaceAll(String) / replaceFirst(String) → replace matched parts

* String Class Convenience Methods
   Java’s String has built-in regex support:

  - matches(String regex)
  - split(String regex)
  - replaceAll(String regex, String replacement)
  - replaceFirst(String regex, String replacement)

* Pitfalls & Best Practices
  - Escape backslashes: "\\d" not "\d"
  - Compile once, reuse: Avoid recompiling the same pattern repeatedly in loops
  - Beware of catastrophic backtracking: Complex patterns on long inputs can hang
  - Use raw strings? → Not in Java (until Java 21+ with preview feature for raw string literals—but still not standard for regex)
  - Validate input: Regex alone isn’t enough for complex validations (e.g., email, URL)

* Practical Use Cases
  - Input validation (emails, phone numbers, ZIP codes)
  - Log parsing
  - Data extraction (e.g., scraping patterns from text)
  - Search-and-replace operations
  - Tokenizing strings
